article.headline: Sun's starters hit double digits in win over Storm
article.linkText: Sun's starters hit double digits in win over Storm
article.story:
UNCASVILLE, Conn. (AP) -- Katie Douglas had both ends of her game
working Friday night.

The Connecticut guard had 18 points, four steals and helped shut
down Seattle's Sue Bird to lead the Sun to an 85-81 win over the
Storm on Friday night.

"I ate my Wheaties today," Douglas said. "My coaches have me
prepared on (Bird's) tendencies so I'm prepared for the game."

Her night included two picks on Bird and she finished both off
with a breakaway lefty layup.

All five starters for Connecticut finished in double figures and
the Sun (6-1) never trailed, leading by as many as 12 early.

Janelle Burse had season highs of 23 points and 14 rebounds for
Seattle, which has lost its last four games at Connecticut,
including the 2004 WNBA championship series opener. They split
their two-game series last year, with Seattle winning on its home
court. The Storm were the only Western Conference team to beat the
Sun in the regular season in 2005.

Connecticut was without starting post player Taj
McWilliams-Franklin, who is in Italy this weekend to attend the
high school graduation of her daughter, Michele. She had been
averaging 11 points and 9.5 boards a game.

In her absence, the Sun's reserve post players and starting
center, 7-foot-2 Margo Dydek, picked up the slack.

Reserve forward Asjha Jones, who finished with 14 points,
started in her place and helped get the Sun off to a quick start.
Dydek grabbed 12 rebounds and finished with 14 points.

"Considering we shot 41 percent, that was a pretty good win,"
Sun coach Mike Thibault said. "No Taj. Our bench struggled
scoring, although I thought they played well defensively."

Connecticut led 25-13 after the first quarter. Burse and Lauren
Jackson brought the Storm (4-4) back in the second and the Sun's
lead was cut to nine by halftime.

But by the time Seattle found its rhythm it was too late.

"We stayed behind for so long that when we really tried to get
after it and get a win it was too late," Seattle coach Ann Donovan
said. "Connecticut's too good to just fold."

Douglas' defense on Bird helped hold the All-Star point guard
scoreless until there were 48 seconds left in the game. Bird's
pull-up jumper got the Storm to within five at 78-73. Bird had a
season-high 10 assists but finished with a season-low two points.

"She's a really good defender. She's tough to play against,"
Bird said. "But I still think I could have made a lot of those
shots."

All Seattle could do the rest of the way was foul. The Sun iced
it at the line, hitting nine of 10 in the final minute.

Nykesha Sales and Lindsay Whalen had 17 points each for
Connecticut. Whalen made 11 of 12 from the free-throw line, including
the last two to seal the win.

Jackson scored 17 for the Storm and Betty Lennox added 12.
Rookie Barbara Turner finished with a season-high 13 points for
Seattle. The former UConn star was making her professional debut in
Connecticut and many of the current Huskies were in attendance.
Jackson scored 17.

"The first five minutes of the game killed us," Jackson said.
"If we played the first five minutes like the last five minutes,
we would have been OK."
